Examining the Relationship Between Different Economic Indicators and their Effect of Economic Output from 1954 to 2019¶

Julianna Dorsch¶

The purpose of this project is to explore the interactions between different economic factors and how they affect the economic health of the United States.

Background:¶

Americans suffer hardships when the economic health of the country is poor but benefit when the economic health of the country is strong. Therefore, it is important to better understand the various economic factors that affect the health of the economy and how they interact with each other. This way, economists might be able to advise and warn of looming economic hardship and recommend ways the government or the Federal Reserve can intervene to prevent economic downturns. The economic indicators this research will be examining are the unemployment rate, the inflation rate, the interest rate, median family income, the Dow Jones Industrial Average (DJIA), and the Gross Domestic Product (GDP). The unemployment rate is the percentage of the workforce that does not have a job, the inflation rate is the rate at which prices for goods and services are rising, the interest rate is the rate at which banks borrow from each other, the DJIA is a stock market index tracking the overall strength of the stock market, and GDP is the sum of consumption, investment, government spending, and net exports of a country for a given time period.

There are generally accepted relationships between these different indicators. The unemployment rate and inflation typically have an inverse relationship (Unemployment and Inflation). This can be explained by the fact that when unemployment is high, typically wages are low because employers can attract workers to work for a low wage. Low wages correspond with low prices, meaning inflation is lower. The opposite explanation applies for explaining the relationship between low unemployment and high inflation. Unemployment and GDP also have an inverse relationship (Unemployment and GDP). High unemployment means there is less output, resulting in lower GDP, and vice versa. Inflation and GDP are directly related (Inflation and GDP), and this can be caused by a variety of scenarios, one being that a higher demand causes higher prices, meaning inflation and GDP both are higher. Interest rates and GDP also have a direct relationship (Interest Rates and GDP), as with a higher GDP, the demand for money increases, which results in a higher interest rate. Income and GDP also have a direct relationship (Income and GDP%20measures,economy%20in%20a%20given%20period.)) because part of GDP is determined by consumer spending and with higher income, there is more consumer consumption. Lastly, the DJIA and GDP are also directly related because increases in the DJIA cause increase in confidence, which will cause increase in spending and therefore GDP (DJIA and GDP). During this research, these indicators will be examined to determine if the levels of these indicators affect the level of other indicators. The strength of these relationships will also be examined. Additionally, this research will examine if a regression line can be found that relates GDP to the other indicators, or the other indicators to each other. By doing so, economists will be more effective in warning about economic recessions.

Questions to be Answered:¶

  • Is there a difference in the Real Median Family Income Growth Rate, the Inflation Rate, the Unemployment Rate, the Interest Rate, and the Growth of the DJIA when GDP growth is above the typical growth rate versus when GDP growth is below the typical growth rate?
  • Is there a difference in GDP growth rate when each of Real Median Family Income Growth Rate, the Inflation Rate, the Unemployment Rate, the Interest Rate, and the Growth of the DJIA are above their typical respective values versus when they are below their typical respective values?
  • Is it possible to find a regression line to describe the relationship between these different economic indicators?

Dataset¶

The data for the dataset was obtained from a variety of websites:

  • Unemployment Rate Since 1948 This data comes from the U.S. Department of Labor, which tracks employment in the U.S.
  • Inflation Rate Since 1914 This source uses information from the Bureau of Labor Statistics to compute the inflation rate for each year.
  • Interest Rate Since 1950 This data comes from the Federal Reserve, who sets interest rates.
  • Dow Jones Industrial Average Historical Prices 1 This data comes from the Wall Street Journal, which has historically tracked the health of the stock market.
  • Dow Jones Industrial Average Historical Prices 2 This data comes from the Federal Reserve, who also takes an interest in the health of the stock market.
  • Dow Jones Industrial Average Historical Prices 3 This data comes from a source dedicated to tracking trends in the economy.
  • Real GDP This data comes from the Federal Reserve, who also takes an interest in total economic output.
  • Real Median Family Income This data comes from the Federal Reserve, who also takes an interest in the level of income of Americans.

Data Cleaning¶

The CSV files were downloaded from these websites. The data was then merged into one data frame. To briefly summarize this process, this analysis examined quarterly data, so if there was more frequent data in some datasets then quarterly, the extra values were eliminated. If the dataset only had yearly data, the missing data was filled in by using a simple linear relationship between the two years, as it was assumed that the change during that short period of time was roughly linear.

The details of this process can be found here: Cleaning Data

The final data was accumulated into a csv file called cleandata.csv.

Notes About the Data¶

There are two different types of values in economics: nominal and real values. Nominal values are the values that are seen whether it be dollar amount or a percentage representing a rate. Real values are the nominal values that have been adjusted for inflation Real vs. Nominal. For example, say the price of a house was 50,000 dollars in 1950. In 1990, the price of the same house is 120,000 dollars. This does not necessarily mean that the value of the house more than doubled in 40 years, because the value of the dollar changes as time progresses. So, if a dollar in 1950 is equivalent to two dollars in 1990, the price of the house in terms of 1950 dollar value is 60,000 dollars, which tells a much different story. Instead of the house more than doubling in value, it only increased by 20%. 120,000 is the nominal value of the house, while 60,000 is the real value of the house. This analysis will use real values, as they consider the effects of inflation.

As can be seen in the title, this analysis only goes up to 2019. The decision was made to stop at 2019 and not include 2020 because of the unique economic events that took place in 2020 due to COVID-19. In March 2020, the government shut down the economy and artificially sent the U.S. economy into a recession due to both a lack of supply and demand. This type of recession is very unique and the economic events that are still occurring today are not typical by economic standards. In that view, it could be considered that the year 2020 is an outlier, and therefore should not be included in the analysis.

def calculatePercent(data):
    vals = [0]
    for i in range(len(data) - 1):
        val = round((data[i + 1] - data[i]) / data[i] * 100, 2)
        vals = vals + [val]
    return vals
data = pd.DataFrame(pd.read_csv('data/cleandata.csv'))
data['Real Median Family Income'] = calculatePercent(data['Real Median Family Income'])
data['Value of Dow'] = calculatePercent(data['Value of Dow'])
data['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['Date'])
data = data.set_index('Date')
data.columns = ['GDP Growth', 'Real Median Family Income Growth', 'Inflation Rate', 'Unemployment Rate', 'Interest Rate', 'Dow Growth']

Is there a difference in the Real Median Family Income Growth Rate, the Inflation Rate, the Unemployment Rate, the Interest Rate, and the Growth of the DJIA when GDP growth is above the typical growth rate versus when GDP growth is below the typical growth rate?¶

The above question is important to consider because answering it could reveal the effects that either slow or fast GDP growth have on other economic indicators such as family income, inflation, unemployment, the interest rate, and the DJIA. Economists often argue that higher or lower economic output, that is higher or lower GDP growth, has various effects on factors such as the ones described above. The following analysis will address if changes in GDP do have an impact on these indicators and to what extent is the effect of the change in GDP.

Before this question is addressed, the smaller question of what is the typical GDP growth rate in the U.S. needs to be answered. An average year of economic growth is considered to be growth of 2% (1). Therefore, this analysis will consider the different economic indicators when GDP growth was above 2% versus when it was below 2%.

#Forming DataFrames that have the values for when GDP growth was above 2 and when it was below
aboveGDP = data[data['GDP Growth'] >= 2.0]
belowGDP = data[data['GDP Growth'] < 2.0]

The following function will perform three main tasks. First, it will plot the distribution for a given economic indicator for all values of GDP, for values when GDP Growth was greater than 2%, and for values when GDP Growth was less than 2%. Second, it will show the normality test for these distributions. As will be seen in the results, nearly all of these distributions are not normally distributed. Because of the lack of normality, the mannwhitneyu test will be used to test if there is a difference of means for the data with GDP growth above 2% and the data with GDP growth below 2%. The test statistic and p-value will be outputted. If there is a statistically significant difference, the means of each group will be printed.

def aboveBelowGDP(data0, data1, data2, name):
    fig, (ax0, ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=3, sharex=False, figsize=(15, 6))
    ax0.set_title('All GDP Growth Values') 
    ax0.hist(data0[name])
    ax0.set_ylabel('Frequency')
    ax0.set_xlabel('Percentage Growth')
    ax1.set_title("When GDP Growth Above 2%") 
    ax1.hist(data1[name])
    ax1.set_ylabel('Frequency')
    ax1.set_xlabel('Percentage Growth')
    ax2.set_title('When GDP Growth Below 2%') 
    ax2.hist(data2[name])
    ax2.set_ylabel('Frequency')
    ax2.set_xlabel('Percentage Growth')
    tit = name + ' from 1954 to 2019'
    fig.suptitle(tit)
    fig.subplots_adjust(wspace=.5)
    fig.subplots_adjust(hspace=.35)
    plt.show()
    print("Normality Test for All GDP Growth Values:           ", stats.shapiro(data0[name]))
    print("Normality Test for when GDP Growth Values Above 2%: ", stats.shapiro(data1[name]))
    print("Normality Test for when GDP Growth Values Below 2%: ", stats.shapiro(data2[name]))
    print()
    st, p = stats.mannwhitneyu(data1[name], data2[name])
    print("Mannwhitneyu Test for Differences of Means for Above and Below 2%: ", stats.mannwhitneyu(data1[name], data2[name]))
    print()
    if(p < 0.05):
        print("There is a statistically significant difference between the" , name, "when GDP growth is below 2% versus above 2%.")
        print()
        print("Mean for ", name, "when GDP growth is above 2%: ",  statistics.mean(data1[name]))
        print("Mean for ", name, "when GDP growth is below 2%: ",  statistics.mean(data2[name]))
        print()
        print("The p-value is: ", p)
    else:
        print("There is no statistically significant difference between the " , name, " when GDP growth is below 2% versus above 2%.")

If the p-value is less than 0.05, it can be concluded that there is a statistically significant difference between the groups. If the value is greater, this cannot be concluded, and there is a failure to reject the null hypothesis that the averages are the same. There were statistically significant differences when comparing the values for real median family income growth, the inflation rate, and the growth in the DJIA. For real median family income growth, when GDP growth was above 2%, the average growth in real median family income was 0.41%, while when GDP growth was less than 2%, the average growth in real median family income was 0.17%. For the inflation rate, when GDP growth was above 2%, the average inflation rate was 3.11%, while when GDP growth was less than 2%, the average inflation rate was 4.39%. For DJIA growth, when GDP growth was above 2%, the average DJIA growth was 3.05%, while when GDP growth was less than 2%, the average DJIA growth was -0.20%.

These statistics suggest that on average during more rapid economic growth, real median family income grows at a faster rate, inflation is slower, and the DJIA grows at a faster rate when compared to when there are periods of slower economic growth. The results of real median family income growth and GDP growth does agree with the notion that income and GDP have a direct relationship, as it would be expected that when the economy is producing more and is healthier, individuals have more income to spend. The results of inflation do not agree with the trend that inflation and GDP have a direct relationship, as when GDP growth was higher, the average inflation rate was slower when compared to the average inflation rate when GDP growth was slower. This could perhaps be explained that when the economy is experiencing slow growth, actions are often taken by the government and Federal Reserve to stimulate the economy. The government could spend money while the Federal Reserve could lower interest rates. Both actions will result in a lower value of the dollar, causing the inflation rate to increase (1). This would mean that there could be a higher inflation rate when there is slow GDP growth. The results of the growth in the DJIA do agree with the trend that the DJIA and GDP have a direct relationship, as it would be expected that when the economy is in poorer health, investors are more cautious and invest less in the stock market, meaning the value of the DJIA is lower.

Some cautionary statements with the analysis above include that these results are dependent on the typical value. If a value lower or higher than 2% is chosen and this analysis is repeated, there could be different results. 2% was chosen because 2% is considered to be average growth according to Blanchard (1). Different economists might think a different number is more appropriate. Additionally, this analysis did not consider the variance caused by the cyclical nature of the economy.

Is there a difference in GDP growth rate when each of Real Median Family Income Growth Rate, the Inflation Rate, the Unemployment Rate, the Interest Rate, and the Growth of the DJIA are above their typical respective values versus when they are below their typical respective values?¶

The above question is important to consider because answering it could reveal the effects of changes to income, inflation, unemployment, the interest rate, and the DJIA have on GDP. Economists often argue that certain changes to these factors will cause either higher or lower GDP growth. The following analysis will address if changes in these factors do effect GDP and to what extent is GDP impacted.

Before this question is addressed, the smaller question of what are the typical values for each of these factors in the U.S. needs to be answered. According to Blanchard (1), the following can be considered typical values:

  • Median Family Income Growth: 0%
  • Inflation: 2%
  • Interest Rate: 2%
  • Unemployment Rate: 4.5%
  • Dow Jones Industrial Average Growth: 0% This analysis will consider GDP growth when each of these economic factors were above and below these typical values.

The following function will perform three main tasks. First, it will plot the distribution of GDP growth for a given economic factor for all values of the economic factor, for values when the economic factor is greater than the typical value, and for values when the economic factor was less than the typical value. Second, it will show the normality test for these distributions. As will be seen in the results, nearly all of these distributions are not normally distributed. Because of the lack of normality, the mannwhitneyu test will be used to test if there is a difference of means for the GDP when the economic factor had a value above the typical value and the GDP when the economic factor had a value below the typical value. The test statistic and p-value will be outputted. If there is a statistically significant difference, the means of each group will be printed.

def aboveBelowOther(data0, data1, data2, name, criticalVal):
    fig, (ax0, ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=3, sharex=False, figsize=(15, 6))
    tit1 = 'All ' + name + ' Values' 
    ax0.set_title(tit1) 
    ax0.hist(data0['GDP Growth'])
    ax0.set_ylabel('Frequency')
    ax0.set_xlabel('Percentage Growth')
    tit2 = "When " + name + " Above " + str(criticalVal) + "%"
    ax1.set_title(tit2) 
    ax1.hist(data1['GDP Growth'])
    ax1.set_ylabel('Frequency')
    ax1.set_xlabel('Percentage Growth')
    tit3 = "When " + name + " Below " + str(criticalVal) + "%"
    ax2.set_title(tit3) 
    ax2.hist(data2['GDP Growth'])
    ax2.set_ylabel('Frequency')
    ax2.set_xlabel('Percentage Growth')
    tit = 'GDP Growth from 1954 to 2019'
    fig.suptitle(tit)
    fig.subplots_adjust(wspace=.5)
    fig.subplots_adjust(hspace=.35)
    plt.show()
    stat1 = "Normality Test for when " + name + " Values Above " + str(criticalVal)+ "%: "
    print("Normality Test for All", name, "Values: ", stats.shapiro(data0['GDP Growth']))
    print(stat1, stats.shapiro(data1['GDP Growth']))
    stat2 = "Normality Test for when " + name + " Values Below " + str(criticalVal)+ "%: "
    print(stat2, stats.shapiro(data2['GDP Growth']))
    print()
    st, p = stats.mannwhitneyu(data1['GDP Growth'], data2['GDP Growth'])
    stat1 = "Mannwhitneyu Test for Differences of Means for Above and Below " + str(criticalVal) + "%: "
    print(stat1, stats.mannwhitneyu(data1['GDP Growth'], data2['GDP Growth']))
    print()
    if(p < 0.05):
        stat1 = "There is a statistically significant difference between the GDP Growth when " + name + " is below " + str(criticalVal) + "% versus above " + str(criticalVal) + "%."
        print(stat1)
        print()
        stat2 = "Mean for GDP Growth when " + name + " is above " + str(criticalVal) + "%: "
        print(stat2,  statistics.mean(data1['GDP Growth']))
        stat1 = "Mean for GDP Growth when " + name + " is below " + str(criticalVal) + "%: "
        print(stat1,  statistics.mean(data2['GDP Growth']))
        print()
        print("The p-value is: ", p)
    else:
        stat1 = "There is no statistically significant difference between the GDP Growth when " + name + " is below " + str(criticalVal) + "% versus above " + str(criticalVal) + "%."
        print(stat1)

The p-value is:  0.002862663613383836

If the p-value is less than 0.05, it can be concluded that there is a statistically significant difference between the sets. If the value is greater, this cannot be concluded, and there is a failure to reject the null hypothesis that the averages are the same. There were statistically significant differences when comparing the values of GDP for real median family income growth, the interest rate, and the growth in the DJIA. For real median family income growth, when real median family income growth was above 0%, the average growth in GDP was 3.52%, while when real median family income growth was less than 0%, the average growth in GDP was 2.27%. For the interest rate, when the interest rate was above 2%, the average growth in GDP was 3.23%, while when the interest rate was less than 2%, the average growth in GDP was 2.50%. For DJIA growth, when the DJIA growth was above 0%, the average GDP growth was 3.54%, while when the DJIA growth was less than 0%, the average DJIA growth was 2.26%.

These statistics suggest that when there is a higher level of real median family income, higher interest rates, and higher levels of the DJIA, GDP growth is higher. The results of real median family income growth and GDP growth does agree with the notion that income and GDP have a direct relationship, as it would be expected that when individuals have more income, they spend more money and cause economic growth through their spending. The results of the interest rate and GDP growth do agree with the trend that interest rates and GDP have a direct relationship, as when interest rates are higher, lenders are willing to lend more money, meaning there is an increase in investment and therefore higher GDP growth. The results of the growth in the DJIA do agree with the trend that the DJIA and GDP have a direct relationship, as it would be expected that when the DJIA is higher, companies have more capital to invest and grow, which would increase economic output.

Some cautionary statements with the analysis above include that these results are dependent on the typical values used. If values lower or higher are chosen and this analysis is repeated, there could be different results. These values were chosen because they were considered to be the typical values according to Blanchard (1). Different economists might think a different number is more appropriate. Additionally, this analysis did not consider the variance caused by the cyclical nature of the economy.

In both of the previous two questions, there was no significant difference when comparing the different groups with respect to unemployment. According to this analysis, this would indicate that there is no significant difference in average unemployment when GDP growth is rapid versus when it is slow, and there is no significant difference in GDP growth when unemployment is high versus when it is low. These results are not what I expected, as to have economic output, there must be individuals to do the work. However, this analysis seems to reflect that the unemployment rate does not affect GDP growth. Perhaps this could be explained by how the unemployment rate is measured. The unemployment rate is calculated by using the number of people looking for a job (Calculating Unemployment Rate). This means that the unemployment rate excludes people who have given up hope at finding a job, which would happen in times of economic hardship. This could mean that the unemployment rate when GDP growth is slow is lower than it actually should be. If this were considered, perhaps statistically significant results would be obtained.

Is it possible to find a regression line to describe the relationship between these different economic indicators?¶

The third question is important to address because if a regression line can be found, it could be helpful in determining future trends of the health of the U.S. economy. It will also be helpful in determining what is the overall shape of the relationship between these different economic indicators. The patterns that will be examined are linear, quadratic, and cubic.

When initially examining the scatter plots of GDP compared to the other indicators, it seemed highly doubtful that one would be able to obtain a good regression line. Therefore, it was investigated if regression lines between different economic indicators could be found. The relationships that were examined were:

  • Unemployment vs. Interest Rate
  • Unemployment vs. Income
  • Inflation vs. Income
  • Inflation vs. Unemployment
  • Inflation vs. Interest Rate

The following function will perform two tasks. First, it will find the strength of the correlation between these different groups. As discussed previously, the data is not normally distributed, so the Spearman Rank-Order Test will be used. It will then attempt to fit the data with a linear, quadratic, and cubic model, and will output the Coefficient of Determination and coefficients for each model. The fits will be plotted on a scatter plot.

def correlateAndFit(data0, name1, name2):
    cor, p = stats.spearmanr(data0[name1], data0[name2])
    print("The p-value of the spearmanr test for ", name1, "and", name2, "was", p)
    print("The correlation coefficient for ", name1, "and", name2, "was", cor)
    print()
    print()
    x=data0[name1]
    y=data0[name2]
    plt.scatter(x, y, color="black")
    plt.xlabel(name1)
    plt.ylabel(name2)
    tit = name1 + " and " + name2 + " from 1954 to 2019"
    plt.title(tit)
    model_linear=LinearRegression(fit_intercept=True)
    model_squared=LinearRegression(fit_intercept=True)
    model_cubic=LinearRegression(fit_intercept=True)
    x2=x**2
    x3=x**3
    model_linear.fit(np.vstack([x]).T, y)
    model_squared.fit(np.vstack([x,x2]).T, y)
    model_cubic.fit(np.vstack([x,x2,x3]).T, y)
    yf_linear=model_linear.predict(np.vstack([x]).T)
    yf_squared=model_squared.predict(np.vstack([x,x2]).T)
    yf_cubic=model_cubic.predict(np.vstack([x,x2,x3]).T)
    plt.plot(x,yf_linear, label="Linear")
    plt.plot(x,yf_squared, label="Quadratic")
    plt.plot(x,yf_cubic, label="Cubic")
    linr = model_linear.score(np.vstack([x]).T, y)
    quadr = model_squared.score(np.vstack([x,x2]).T, y)
    cubr = model_cubic.score(np.vstack([x,x2,x3]).T, y)
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()
    print()
    coef = "The Coefficients of Determination were:\nLinear: " + str(linr) + "\nQuadratic: " + str(quadr) + "\nCubic: " + str(cubr) 
    print(coef)
    print()
    print()
    lin = "Linear Model Coefficients and Intercept:\nIntercept: " + str(model_linear.intercept_) + "\nCoefficients: " + str(model_linear.coef_)
    print(lin)
    print()
    quad = "Quadratic Model Coefficients and Intercept:\nIntercept: " + str(model_squared.intercept_) + "\nCoefficients: " + str(model_squared.coef_)
    print(quad)
    print()
    quad = "Cubic Model Coefficients and Intercept:\nIntercept: " + str(model_cubic.intercept_) + "\nCoefficients: " + str(model_cubic.coef_)
    print(quad)
    print()
    print()
    print()

If the p-value is less than 0.05, it can be concluded that there is a statistically significant correlation between the groups. If the value is greater, this cannot be concluded, and there is a failure to reject the null hypothesis that there is no correlation. There is no statistically significant correlation between the unemployment and interest rates. Meanwhile, unemployment and income, inflation and income, inflation and unemployment, and inflation and interest rates all had a statistically significant correlation. Therefore, the fits for these relationships will be analyzed more closely.

There was a negative relationship between income and unemployment. This would agree with my expectations because as unemployment rises, more people are unemployed, and therefore have less income. When examining the three different fits, the quadratic and cubic models are nearly straight lines, which would lead to the conclusion that the relationship between income and unemployment is linear.

There was a slight negative relationship between income and inflation. This would agree with my expectations, because as inflation rises, the real income of individuals will fall because money is worth less with higher rates of inflation. When examining the three different fits, the quadratic and cubic models are nearly straight lines, which would lead to the conclusion that the relationship between income and inflation is linear.

The relationship between inflation and unemployment is slightly more complicated. The Spearman Rank-Order test stated that the relationship was slightly positive. However, when examining the fits, the cubic model had the highest value for the Coefficient of Determination, meaning it was the best fit. Also, it can be observed that the cubic model does exhibit clear cubic behavior. It would be reasonable that the relationship between inflation and unemployment was cubic, as when there is negative inflation, there is often negative economic growth and high levels of unemployment. However, when the inflation rate increases and is around 2%, unemployment is lower, which would reflect the low positive inflation rates are associated with a healthy economy and therefore with a healthier level of unemployment. However, if the inflation rate becomes too high, the cost to businesses will increase, making it harder for them to keep workers, which would raise the unemployment rate. This follows cubic behavior. However, it is also important to acknowledge the value of the Coefficient of Determination was low, meaning the fit was not great.

There is a strong positive relationship between inflation and the interest rate. This would also agree with my expectations, because when inflation increases, the Federal Reserve will often respond and combat the rise in inflation with higher interest rates. When examining the three different fits, the quadratic and cubic models are nearly straight lines, which would lead to the conclusion that the relationship between inflation and the interest rate is linear.

Some cautionary statements would be that except for the relationship between inflation and the interest rate, the fits for these relationships were not the best. This would suggest that there are other factors that influence these relationships that were not considered in this analysis. In a future study, perhaps these factors could be found and included in the fit. Additionally, this fit was not dependent on time in anyway, which could be a factor as the economy is often cyclical in nature.

Conclusions and Discussions¶

The statistical analysis showed that there is a statistically significant difference in the averages of real median family income, inflation, and the DJIA when comparing these values when GDP growth is less than 2% versus when it is greater than 2%. The analysis also demonstrated that there is a statistically significant difference in the average GDP growth when comparing the value when the growth of real median family income is greater than and less than 0%, when the interest rate is greater than and less than 2%, and when the growth in the DJIA is greater than and less than 0%. Income and the DJIA being in both groups reflect that the amount of GDP growth will affect the values of income and the DJIA and that the values of income and the DJIA could contribute to the level of GDP growth. The presence of a statistically significant difference in the average inflation rate when GDP growth is less than 2% versus when it is greater than 2% suggest that inflation is reactionary to the health of the economy and not necessarily a forecaster for economic health, as inflation was demonstrated to be changed depending on the growth of GDP. On the other hand, the presence of a statistically significant difference in the average GDP growth when the interest rate is greater than and less than 2% suggest that the interest rate can be a forecaster of economic health, as it was demonstrated that the growth in GDP changed depending on the interest rate. The correlation tests and fitting demonstrated that when there is a relationship between these indicators, it tends to be slight and linear, except for the relationship between inflation and the interest rate. This lack of strong relationships could be the result of factors that were not included in the analysis. These factors could include time, expectations, and the overall cyclical nature of the economy. In future analyses, these factors should be utilized. Additionally, this analysis could be conducted with monthly, biyearly, or yearly data instead of quarterly data. Analysis using this data could perhaps yield different results. The results could also be different if different typical values are used in the analysis comparing the averages of different economic indicators.

Ethics¶

This research is studying the U.S. economy, which directly impacts the standard of living of every American, so any research conducted should be done cautiously. The overall purpose of this research is to determine if trends can be tracked in the overall economy so that future economic downturns can be predicted and therefore prevented through government or Federal Reserve intervention. This research could be used by individuals who after predicting a financial downturn, are then able to change their financial situation so that they are not as severely negatively impacted by the downturn. This could also be used by government officials to help ensure that the overall quality of life for Americans does not decrease by trying to either dampen or fully prevent the effects of the downturn when it is forecasted. However, this research could also be potentially used by people or groups wishing to exploit individuals. With the knowledge of a potential economic downturn, these people and groups could exploit unaware individuals, thereby strengthening their financial situation while harming individuals who then would be even more exposed to the effects of a recession.
